The pitcher ordered the cap about a month ago and wore it while playing catch over the past week.

'The difference between how this hat and the regular hat feels isn't much,' Torres said.

'I tried it before using it in the game, playing catch. It doesn't feel really bad. It doesn't feel like how it looks on my head.'

The heavier and bigger hat, introduced this year following a spate of terrifying and bloody head injuries in the last few years, was tested by volunteers.

